c. In order to make a right comparison between the values of earning in 2008 and 1992, we should adjust adjust the average hourly earnings in the 1992 dollars to the 2008 dollars with the inflation rate, computed as

$$\frac{CPI_{2008}}{CPI_{1992}}$$

Consider that those values are equal to 140.3 for 1992 and 215.2 for 2008. Repeat the item above consering this adjusted value for 1992.

In [103]:
# Define the CPI values for 1992 and 2008
cpi_92 = 140.3
cpi_08 = 215.2

# Calculate the inflation adjustment factor
inflator = cpi_08 / cpi_92

# Apply inflation adjustment to the 'ahe' column
df.loc[df['year'] == 1992, 'ahe'] = df.loc[df['year'] == 1992, 'ahe'] * inflator
# your answer goes here
print(df)

Pre data: I picked testscore and student to teacher ratio because I assume that a student's test score would be correlated to how many teachers are in the school. My prediction is that when the str increases, the student's test score would go down, meaning there is a negative correlation because more teaxhers mean that there is less individualized attention per student. Post-data: My data shows that for every unit increase in the student teacher ratio, the test score drops by around 2.25%. This matches my previous prediction of there being a negative correlation between these variables.
